<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-396-782  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 396 782.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  June 26 1989 n544 pT10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The open integration paradox. (in design automation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burich, Misha R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Integrated design systems and point-solution tools used to beincompatible, both as goals and as technologies.andP;  Now, integrateddesign systems can be tightly designed to the user's changingintegrated circuit design needs.andP;  The result is computer-aideddesign (CAD) that combines the convenience of automation with thecontrol factor of point-solution tools tailored to therequirements of graphical, database and algorithmic programs.andO;This integration of integrated circuit design tools provides ameans of managing vast amounts of created data, which can be evenlarger in non-integrated systems.andP;  Using the integrated designapproach, productivity can be enhanced by the creation of aunified environment combining logic synthesis, mixed-modesimulation, test vector generation and other features.andP;  A leaderin the application of this technology is Silicon Compiler SystemsCorp, with their SCS Foundation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Silicon Compiler Systems Inc. (product development).andO;Topic:     Integrated SystemsComputer-Aided DesignTechnologyIntegrated CircuitsData Base Management Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Silicon Compiler Systems Corp's integrated chip design foundation.andO;(table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>